
CHAPTER XX.

FOR some days after that evening, Mr. Heath-
cliff shunned meeting us at meals; yet he
would not consent, formally, to exclude Hare-
ton and Cathy. He had an aversion to yield-
ing so completely to his feelings, chosing, ra-
ther, to absent himself--And eating once in
twenty-four hours seemed sufficient sustenance
for him.

One night, after the family were in bed, I
heard him go down stairs, and out at the front
door: I did not hear him re-enter
